---
description: Enforce core coding and architecture principles
alwaysApply: true
---

# Core Principles

- Keep implementations as simple as possible and avoid over-engineering.
- Optimize for readability with clear naming and comments that explain why.
- Enforce DRY by extracting repeated business logic and UI markup.
- Ask user permission before major revisions and include the reason.

# Frontend (Next.js + React)

- Use function components and hooks.
- Prefer server components/actions when project uses Next.js.
- Organize by feature with `actions/`, `app/`, `components/`, `hooks/`, `services/`, `types/`, `lib/`.
- Use accessible markup and `shadcn/ui` for UI components when applicable.
- Keep Tailwind classes readable and multiline for complex styles.

# Backend (NestJS)

- Keep controllers thin and business logic in services.
- Use dependency injection, DTOs, class-validator, and RESTful naming.
- Handle errors with NestJS exception filters.

# Database (Prisma + PostgreSQL)

- Use schema-first modeling and migrations for changes.
- Prefer type-safe queries and transactions for multi-step writes.

# Testing and Security

- Use Jest (backend), React Testing Library (frontend), and Playwright/Cypress (e2e).
- Keep files focused on one responsibility and consistent naming.
- Use `.env` for configuration, never commit secrets, and validate env vars at startup.
